ene transcription","Inhibits tyrosine kinase synthesis","Blocks ATP binding site on tyrosine kinases","Degrades tyrosine kinase","Activates protein phosphatases"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETyrosine kinase inhibitors function by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking ATP binding sites on tyrosine kinases\u003C/strong\u003E This prevents tyrosine kinase phosphorylation, thereby inhibiting downstream signalling pathways involved in cell growth and survival.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this mechanism explains why the other options are incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of tyrosine kinase inhibitors include imatinib for chronic myeloid leukaemia and erlotinib for epidermal growth factor receptor-mutated lung cancer. These drugs are identified by the suffix \u0027-nib\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tyrosine kinase inhibitors work by blocking ATP binding sites on tyrosine kinases, preventing their phosphorylation and downstream signalling.","The suffix \u0027-nib\u0027 identifies a drug as a tyrosine kinase inhibitor.","Tyrosine kinase inhibitors are important targeted therapies in cancer treatment, particularly for tumours with specific molecular mutations."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62183"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62183"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"